hands_on_practices.solution:
The McDonald-Kreitman framework estimates the proportion of adaptive nonsynonymous substitutions as
$$
\alpha \equiv 1 - \frac{P_{n}/P_{s}}{D_{n}/D_{s}} \;=\; 1 - \frac{D_{s} P_{n}}{D_{n} P_{s}}.
$$
To correct for the bias from weakly deleterious polymorphisms, we restrict the polymorphism counts to the common-variant class with derived allele frequency at least 0.15. Denote these as $P_{n}^{\mathrm{high}}$ and $P_{s}^{\mathrm{high}}$. Using the given data, we have $D_{n}=65$, $D_{s}=30$, $P_{n}^{\mathrm{high}}=20$, and $P_{s}^{\mathrm{high}}=30$. The corrected estimate is therefore
$$
\alpha_{\mathrm{corr}} \;=\; 1 - \frac{D_{s} P_{n}^{\mathrm{high}}}{D_{n} P_{s}^{\mathrm{high}}}
\;=\; 1 - \frac{30 \cdot 20}{65 \cdot 30}
\;=\; 1 - \frac{20}{65}
\;=\; 1 - \frac{4}{13}
\;=\; \frac{9}{13}.
$$
This is already in simplest fractional form.
